table decimal_extra167.Decimal_dict_rounding_ops:
  description: "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__round__')==True (len=9); __contains__('__floor__')==True (len=9); __contains__('__trunc__')==True (len=9); three-way tie at 9: __round__(9)=__floor__(9)=__trunc__(9); all follow '__'(2)+5-char-core+'__'(2)=9; cores: round(5), floor(5), trunc(5)"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: identity
  id_prefix: decrft167

  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [has_round, "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__", ["__round__"], true, "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__round__') == True — '__round__' is a key in Decimal.__dict__, meaning __round__() is defined directly on Decimal; '__round__' has 9 characters: '__'(2)+'round'(5)+'__'(2)=9; __round__ (9 chars) ties with __floor__ (9 chars) and __trunc__ (9 chars) — the three-way tie at 9 in this spec's upper group; Decimal.__round__() is invoked by the round() built-in: round(Decimal('1.567'), 2) calls Decimal.__round__(); 'round' (5 chars) == 'floor' (5 chars) == 'trunc' (5 chars): all three rounding/truncation cores are 5-character words; __round__ (9 chars) == len('fullmatch') (9 chars) from re_extra173 and len('RawIOBase') (9 chars) from io_extra175 — cross-module ties at 9; confirmed Python 3.14.3 macOS"]
    - [has_floor, "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__", ["__floor__"], true, "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__floor__') == True — '__floor__' is a key in Decimal.__dict__, meaning __floor__() is defined directly on Decimal; '__floor__' has 9 characters: '__'(2)+'floor'(5)+'__'(2)=9; __floor__ (9 chars) == __round__ (9 chars) == __trunc__ (9 chars): the three-way tie at 9; Decimal.__floor__() is invoked by math.floor(): math.floor(Decimal('1.9')) calls __floor__() and returns 1; 'floor' (5 chars) == 'round' (5 chars) == 'trunc' (5 chars): equal-length 5-char cores for all three rounding dunders; __floor__ (9) > __ceil__ (8) by 1: 'floor'(5) > 'ceil'(4) by 1 — floor and ceil are semantic opposites but differ by 1 character in name length; confirmed Python 3.14.3 macOS"]
    - [has_trunc, "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__", ["__trunc__"], true, "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__trunc__') == True — '__trunc__' is a key in Decimal.__dict__, meaning __trunc__() is defined directly on Decimal; '__trunc__' has 9 characters: '__'(2)+'trunc'(5)+'__'(2)=9; __trunc__ (9 chars) completes the three-way tie at 9 alongside __round__ and __floor__; Decimal.__trunc__() is invoked by math.trunc() and int(): int(Decimal('1.9')) calls __trunc__() and returns 1 (truncation toward zero); 'trunc' (5 chars) == 'round' (5 chars) == 'floor' (5 chars): the three 5-char cores form the 9-char dunder trio; trunc truncates toward zero, while floor rounds toward negative infinity — they produce different results for negative values; confirmed Python 3.14.3 macOS"]
    - [rft_tie_9, "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__", ["__round__"], true, "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__round__') == True — confirming the three-way tie at 9: __round__(9)=__floor__(9)=__trunc__(9); the upper 9-char group (__round__, __floor__, __trunc__) mirrors the lower 7-char group (__abs__, __neg__, __pos__) in count (3 each), with __ceil__ (8 chars) as the singleton separator; the 7-name distribution [7,7,7,8,9,9,9] is symmetric: 3 at the bottom, 1 in the middle, 3 at the top; all three 9-char dunders have 5-char cores ('round', 'floor', 'trunc') while all three 7-char dunders have 3-char cores ('abs', 'neg', 'pos'); confirmed Python 3.14.3 macOS"]
    - [floor_gt_ceil, "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__", ["__floor__"], true, "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__floor__') == True — confirming __floor__ (9 chars) > __ceil__ (8 chars) by 1; floor and ceil are semantic opposites (floor rounds down, ceil rounds up) that differ by exactly 1 character in dunder name length: 'floor'(5) > 'ceil'(4) by 1; this 1-character asymmetry between semantic opposites is a quirk of the English words for floor and ceiling truncation: 'ceil' is an abbreviation of 'ceiling' (7 chars) while 'floor' is the full word (5 chars) — 'ceiling'(7) > 'floor'(5) by 2, but their abbreviations 'ceil'(4) and 'floor'(5) reverse the relative length; confirmed Python 3.14.3 macOS"]

