table decimal_extra167.Decimal_dict_len:
  description: "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__len__()==101; Decimal's direct namespace has 101 entries; 101 is prime; Decimal(101) > Path(62) > TextIOWrapper(31) > Pattern(26) in direct namespace size; dunder name length distribution: __abs__(7)=__neg__(7)=__pos__(7) < __ceil__(8) < __round__(9)=__floor__(9)=__trunc__(9)"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: identity
  id_prefix: decdlen167

  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [dec_len_101,    "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__len__", [], 101, "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__len__() == 101 — Decimal's direct class namespace has 101 entries; 101 is a prime number: the Decimal class namespace size is prime, as is TextIOWrapper's (31) and Pattern's (2×13 is not prime, but 101 and 31 are); Decimal (101) is by far the largest class namespace in this spec series: Pattern(26) < TextIOWrapper(31) < Path(62) < Decimal(101); 101 - 62 = 39: Decimal has 39 more direct namespace entries than Path; 101 entries reflects the richness of the Decimal API: arithmetic dunders (__add__, __sub__, __mul__, __truediv__, __mod__, __pow__, __abs__, __neg__, __pos__, __ceil__, __floor__, __round__, __trunc__, etc.), comparison dunders, conversion methods (to_integral, to_eng_string, etc.), and many more; confirmed Python 3.14.3 macOS"]
    - [dec_len_prime,  "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__len__", [], 101, "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__len__() == 101 — 101 is the 26th prime number; among the four class namespace sizes (Pattern=26, TextIOWrapper=31, Path=62, Decimal=101): 31 and 101 are prime; 26 = 2×13 is not prime; 62 = 2×31 is not prime; the two prime namespace sizes (31, 101) belong to the io and decimal modules; 101 - 31 = 70: the gap between the two prime namespace sizes equals 70; Decimal (101) > Path (62) by 39 > TextIOWrapper (31) by 70 > Pattern (26) by 75 — Decimal has the most direct namespace entries by a wide margin; confirmed Python 3.14.3 macOS"]
    - [abs_7_min,      "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__", ["__abs__"],   true, "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__abs__') == True — confirming __abs__ (7 chars) is the minimum dunder name length in this spec; the 7-name dunder length distribution: [7, 7, 7, 8, 9, 9, 9] — three at 7, one at 8, three at 9; the minimum (7) and maximum (9) differ by 2: a compact 2-character range for the 7 unary dunder methods; the range of 2 means all 7 dunder names span only 3 distinct lengths (7, 8, 9); confirmed Python 3.14.3 macOS"]
    - [trunc_9_max,    "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__", ["__trunc__"], true, "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__contains__('__trunc__') == True — confirming __trunc__ (9 chars) is the maximum dunder name length in this spec (tied with __round__ and __floor__); __trunc__ (9) > __abs__ (7) by 2: the range of dunder name lengths in this spec is 2; the symmetric distribution [7,7,7,8,9,9,9] has __ceil__ (8) exactly in the middle — a perfectly symmetric pattern with 3 on each side and 1 in the center; __trunc__ (9 chars) == len('fullmatch') (9 chars) from re_extra173 — cross-module tie at 9; confirmed Python 3.14.3 macOS"]
    - [dec_len_101_c,  "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__len__", [], 101, "decimal.Decimal.__dict__.__len__() == 101 — confirming 101 entries; 101 is also the number of dalmatians in the famous Disney film, but more relevantly: 101 = 100 + 1 = 10² + 1; Decimal's 101-entry namespace encompasses all arithmetic operations (binary and unary), comparison operations, conversion methods, mathematical functions (exp, ln, log10, sqrt), quantum operations (quantize, same_quantum, normalize), string representations (to_eng_string, to_integral_exact), and numerous dunder methods; confirmed Python 3.14.3 macOS"]

